  • Introduction

Introduction¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

Certain columns, like ‘cast’ and ‘genres’, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters.

There are some odd characters in the ‘cast’ column. Don’t worry about cleaning them. You can leave them as is.

The final two columns ending with “_adj” show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

Questions to address.¶

Which genres lead in each category the during the last 5 years?

What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues(adj)?

What is the main insight of the top 10 biggest box office bombs?

What is the main insight of the top 10 box office successes?

# Bin edges that will be used to "cut" the data into groups
bin_edges_bud = [0,1.354637e+07,3.038360e+07,6.084153e+07,4.250000e+08]
bin_edges_rev = [0,1.925371e+07,6.284688e+07,1.658054e+08,2.827124e+09]
# Labels for the four level groups
bin_names = ['Low','Medium','High','Very_High']
In [21]:
# Creates budget and revenue level column
df['budget_level'] = pd.cut(df['budget_adj'], bin_edges_bud, labels=bin_names)
df['revenue_level'] = pd.cut(df['revenue_adj'], bin_edges_rev, labels=bin_names)

Define a new function that splits rows¶

To split rows with multiple cast, genre, and production companies. Create new dataframes for cast, genre, and production companies.

In [22]:
# Define split function
def splitDataFrameList(df,target_column,separator):
    ''' df = dataframe to split,
    target_column = the column containing the values to split
    separator = the symbol used to perform the split
    returns: a dataframe with each entry for the target column separated, with each element moved into a new row. 
    The values in the other columns are duplicated across the newly divided rows.
    '''
    def splitListToRows(row,row_accumulator,target_column,separator):
        split_row = row[target_column].split(separator)
        for s in split_row:
            new_row = row.to_dict()
            new_row[target_column] = s
            row_accumulator.append(new_row)
    new_rows = []
    df.apply(splitListToRows,axis=1,args = (new_rows,target_column,separator))
    new_df = pd.DataFrame(new_rows)
    return new_df

In [58]:

Conclusions¶

Summary Insights¶

Average budget and revenue for a movie is approx. 14.627 million and 39.823 million respectfully.

Highest budget allotted to a film was approx 425 million!

Highest revenue from a film was approx and 2.781 billion!

Movie release years range from 1960 to 2015, with most between 1995 and 2015.

The majority of movies have:¶

a budget between 0-70 million.

revenues between 0-250 million.

recently released, between 1995-2015. during the holiday season.

have runtime between 80-150 minutes.

Movie production has increased over the years but seems to have reached a plateau over the last 5 years.

The cumulative sum of movie budgets has increased over the years but seems to have reached a plateau over the last 5 years. Makes sense since movie production has also increased.

The mean of movie budgets has fluctuated over time. Movies today seem to be cheaper to make compared to those in the 1960's. The mean budget for movies today seems to have settled at around 40 - 45 million dollars.

The sum of movie budget has increased because of the increase of movie production and not because movie are more expensive to make.

The cumulative sum of movie revenue has increased over the years.

Adjusted for inflation, movies raked in more money between the 1960's and 1980's vs today! Interesting...

The sum of movie revenues has increased because of the increase of movie production and not because movie are raking in more money.

Questions Addressed¶

Which genre has lead in each category in the last 5 years?¶

In 4 of the last 5 years Action movies have been the most expensive to produce. Adventure movies over took Action in 2015. Adventure movies has commanded most of the revenues in 4 of the last 5 years with 2014 being the year it fell behind but it quickly bounced back on 2015.

What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues(adj)?¶

Cast¶

Harrison Ford leads with rake in revenue of 14 Billion Dollars! Tom Cruise and Tom Hanks follow with 11 Billion and 10.5 Billion respectfully.

Genres¶

Action, Adventure, Drama, Comedy, and Thriller lead with 210, 200, 175, 160, 150 Billion Dollars respectfully.

Production Companies¶

Warner Bros., Universal Pictures, Paramount Pictures, Twentieth Century, and Walt Disney lead with 67, 61, 54, 50, 37 Billion respectfully.

Directors¶

Steven Spielberg leads with 15 Billion in revenues! James Cameron, Peter Jackson, and George Lucas follow with 7.2, 7.0, 6.2 Billion. Steven has more than double the runner up!

Revenues vs Budgets¶

62.67% of movies with Very_High budgets have Very_High revenues. 62.6% of movies with Very_revenue budget have Very_High budgets.

Does not seem to be a correlation between revenue and budget, there might be a very small positive correlation if any.

Again, no correlation between runtime and revenue but there is a zone, between 80-150 mins is where most of the high revenue movie are clocked.

Properties of top and bottom movies¶

All of the top 10 movies are made up of all if not a combination of high revenue properties.

Every top movie had all or a combination of top cast members (Harrison Ford), genre (Action/Adventure), production company (Warner Bros./20th cent), director (Steven Spielberg), high budget.

All of the bottom 10 movies are made up of non high revenue properties.

Every bottom movie had a combination of bottom cast members (not well known), genre (Romance/Drama), production company (not well known), director (not well known), low-medium budget.

What is the main insight of the top 10 box office successes?¶

Out of the top 10 most successful movies, 7 have had high to very_high budgets (30.3 to 425 Million). You need money to make money...

What are the top 10 biggest box office bombs? (Movies did not generate a profit)¶

Top 10 biggest box office bombs perfectly demonstrates that although most movies with high revenues have high budgets, high budgets don't guarantee high revenues and in fact increases the likely-hood of a BOMB.

Also, I did notice that the director is very important.

The main difference I see between the two lists is directors.

Limitations¶

There was a large amount of data integrity issues due to missing data/values and unknown column origin/explaination. Initially, the data sample was just over 10000 rows but after the cleaning it was reduced to 3800... That's less than half! This reduction in sample space may have caused me to make incorrect conclusions about the box office.
